## From business question to math

Many [[business decisions]] may look straightforward when described in [[abstract]] terms - assigning staff, selecting products, or planning deliveries.

In reality, these tasks are embedded in a messy environment: changing requirements, exceptions, special cases, and conflicting priorities.

Academic examples often strip away this complexity to expose the mathematical core, like turning a real vehicle-routing problem into a clean traveling-salesperson instance. But in practice, all the real-world conditions matter, and even small problems can become too complex for intuition or simple heuristics.

A useful way to introduce structure is to separate the model from the method.

The model captures how the real problem works: the elements involved, the decisions to be made, and the conditions that must hold. It is a representation of the problem itself, not a recipe for how to solve it. Methods or algorithms come later.

By first expressing the decision problem in mathematical terms, we move from informal reasoning to a clear, well-defined model that can serve as the basis for applying optimization techniques.

###   

### Translating the problem: sets, parameters, variables

After identifying the decision problem, the next step is to express its structure using three core elements: sets, parameters, and variables.

- [[Sets]] describe the objects involved: employees, shifts, products, machines, routes. They define the universe in which the model operates.
    
- [[Parameters]] capture the known information: availability of staff, demand for each product, capacity limits, or costs. These are fixed inputs to the model.
    
- [[Variables]] represent the [[decisions]] to be made: how many units to produce, whether a shift is assigned, or which route is chosen. These are the unknowns the solver will determine.
    

The key idea is that we do not write a procedure. We simply declare the elements of the problem and the relationships between them

Once the structure is laid out, we add constraints that encode the business rules.

This set-based, declarative approach makes the model compact, easy to maintain, and directly aligned with the real-world problem.

###   

### A small example: workforce assignment

Consider a simple staff-scheduling problem. A manager needs to assign employees to a small set of shifts. Each shift requires a certain number of people, and each employee has limited availability.

We can describe this in a structured way:

Sets

E: employees  
S: shifts

Parameters

a_e,s: 1 if employee e is available for shift s, otherwise 0  
r_s: number of people needed for shift s  
h_e: maximum number of shifts employee e may work

Variables

x_e,s: 1 if employee e is assigned to shift s, otherwise 0

With these elements, the business rules translate naturally:

Only assign employees who are available:  
xe,s <= ae,s

Cover each shiftâ€™s staffing requirement:

\sum_{e \in E} x_{e,s} \ge r_s

Respect individual limits:  
\sum_{s \in S} x_{e,s} \le h_e

An objective can be chosen depending on the goal - for example, minimizing total assignments or balancing workload.

The important point is that the structure mirrors the business logic. By defining sets and relationships, the model becomes readable, adaptable, and ready for an optimizer to solve.

###   

### Why declarative modeling is powerful

In a [[declarative model]], you describe the rules and relationships that must hold, not the procedure to find a solution. This [[separation of logic from computation]] [[separation of concerns]] is a major advantage.

First, the model remains stable even as the business context changes. Adding new employees, shifts, or constraints does not require rewriting an algorithm; it only means extending the sets or adjusting a few conditions. The structure scales naturally with the size of the problem.

Second, the model is transparent. Each constraint corresponds to a clear business rule, making it easy to review, explain, and audit. This is useful for communicating with stakeholders or validating assumptions.

Third, declarative models are solver-agnostic. Once expressed in algebraic form, they can be handled by a wide range of optimization engines without changing the model itself. The logic stays the same; only the solution technology changes.

This combination of clarity, scalability, and flexibility makes declarative, set-based modeling a robust foundation for building and maintaining optimization solutions.

## Where GAMSPy fits in

Once the problem is expressed in sets, parameters, variables, and constraints, implementing it in code should feel as close as possible to the mathematical formulation.

GAMSPy follows this principle directly.

It provides Python objects for sets and parameters, and lets you write constraints using indexed algebraic expressions rather than low-level loops or control structures to build up a model instance.

  

![](data:image/png;base64,)

As you will notice, the example code above does not contain any function declarations, but is purely declarative in the way the model is set up. You define the elements, state the relationships, and GAMSPy takes care of building a full optimization model behind the scenes. Solver interaction (model generation, solution processing, and handling different solvers) is handled for you, so the focus stays on the logic of the business problem. The advantage is that the structure of the model remains visible in the code. You can find the complete code for the simple example with some minimal data [here](https://gamvzw.clicks.mlsend.com/tb/cl/eyJ2Ijoie1wiYVwiOjUyODU2NixcImxcIjoxNzMyNTUzMjI0MTgyODQyNDgsXCJyXCI6MTczMjkxNTMwNzAxNzY4MDE5fSIsInMiOiI4ZWI5M2FmMjQ4Y2RjNGJkIn0).

In addition to the clarity of this approach you also get the most performance out of it. A system like GAMSPy can optimize the model generation similar to an RDBMS can optimize an SQL query. GAMSPy "sees" the entire model algebra and the data with its sparsity all at once rather than incrementally building up a model instance one variable and one constraint at a time. A [blog post on the GAMS website](https://gamvzw.clicks.mlsend.com/tb/cl/eyJ2Ijoie1wiYVwiOjUyODU2NixcImxcIjoxNzMyNTUzMjI0MjQ1NzU3MDUsXCJyXCI6MTczMjkxNTMwNzAxNzY4MDE5fSIsInMiOiJlYzY4ZTU2OTljNjE1NWM2In0) explains the advantages in much more detail.

The result is a clean path from problem description to mathematical model to computed solution, all expressed in a way that remains close to the original business rules.
